  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       1325 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               1325 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       1325 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     1325 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  1325 1451
VI.1 (Release 3) evaluation by Young [Yo94].                      1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 3 evaluation extends to 40 MeV and        1325 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             1325 1451
significant reactions.  The present evauation utilizes a more     1325 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   1325 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  1325 1451
applications is lost with this representation.  Additionally, we  1325 1451
have modified the neutron reaction cross sections slightly to     1325 1451
improve agreement with data above 20 MeV.                         1325 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    1325 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        1325 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      1325 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   1325 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     1325 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                1325 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   1325 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           1325 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         1325 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      1325 1451
               Deuterons, and Alphas; and Angle-Integrated        1325 1451
               Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual Nuclei That    1325 1451
               Are Stable Against Particle Emission               1325 1451
                                                                  1325 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      1325 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    1325 1451
Al27 and p + Al27 reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system  1325 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               1325 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    1325 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       1325 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     1325 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    1325 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    1325 1451
nuclei are included for reactions that exceed a cross section of  1325 1451
approximately 1 nb at any energy. The energy-angle-correlations   1325 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       1325 1451
[Ka88].                                                           1325 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  1325 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    1325 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  1325 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     1325 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   1325 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  1325 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting..                            1325 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  1325 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      1325 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  1325 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     1325 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     1325 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk [Ig75] and pairing and shell    1325 1451
parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and charged-    1325 1451
particle transmission coefficients were obtained from the         1325 1451
optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray transmission   1325 1451
coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90].  1325 1451
  The neutron total cross section was evaluated from available    1325 1451
experimental data. From 20 - 40 MeV, the existing ENDF/B-VI.3     1325 1451
total cross section evaluation of Young was adopted; from 40 -    1325 1451
150 MeV, the evaluation was based primarily on  Finlay's 1993     1325 1451
measurements [Fi93].  The optical potential of Petler [Pe85],     1325 1451
specially developed for n+Al elastic scattering, was used for     1325 1451
neutrons up to 60 MeV, and above this energy the Madland global   1325 1451
potential [Ma88a] was used. For incident protons, the Petler      1325 1451
neutron potential was modified to account for proton scattering   1325 1451
up to 60 MeV, and again the Madland global potential was used at  1325 1451
higher energies.  For deuterons, the potential of Perey and       1325 1451
Perey [Pe63a] was used at all energies, and for tritons the       1325 1451
Becchetti and Greenlees potential [Be71] was adopted. Finally,    1325 1451
the potential of Arthur and Young [Ar80], based on the work of    1325 1451
Lemos [Le72], was used for alpha particles at all energies. DWBA  1325 1451
calculations were performed for inelastic scattering to low-      1325 1451
lying states using the DWUCK code.                                1325 1451
  While the above optical potentials did describe the             1325 1451
experimental neutron and proton nonelastic cross section data     1325 1451
fairly well, we modified these theoretical predictions slightly   1325 1451
to better agree with the measurements, and renormalized the       1325 1451
transmission coefficients accordingly.                            1325 1451
  The present evaluation was greatly facilitated by Benck et      1325 1451
al.'s [Be98] measurements of charged-particle producing           1325 1451
reactions on Al for incident neutrons at 63 MeV at Louvain-la-    1325 1451
Neuve, Belgium. Since these data represent the only neutron-      1325 1451
induced emission spectra above 20 MeV, they have been invaluable  1325 1451
for guiding, and testing, our calculations.  The proton, triton,  1325 1451
and alpha emission spectra in the Benck et al. measurements are   1325 1451
described very well. However, our deuteron emission calculations  1325 1451
compare poorly with the measurements. Fortunately this has only   1325 1451
a small practical impact since deuteron emission is small         1325 1451
compared to proton emission, and our calculated emission          1325 1451
spectrum approximates the measured deuteron energy deposition     1325 1451
(production cross section times average energy) reasonably well,  1325 1451
which is important for heating calculations. The combination of   1325 1451
equilibrium and preequilibrium reaction mechanisms included in    1325 1451
the GNASH code account for the measured data rather well.         1325 1451
  As an independent validation of our GNASH calculations using    1325 1451
the exciton model, we have also performed FKK calculations. This  1325 1451
was done by implementing a multistep reaction theory recently     1325 1451
developed by Koning and Chadwick, which is particularly suited    1325 1451
to the simultaneous calculation of neutron and proton emission.   1325 1451
The FKK theory describes the forward-peaking very well, as do     1325 1451
our exciton model calculations using the phenomenological         1325 1451
Kalbach angular distribution systematics.                         1325 1451
  As additional validation of the models used in our neutron      1325 1451
evaluation, extensive comparisons were made to higher energy      1325 1451
proton-induced measurements.  In particular, the neutron and      1325 1451
charged-particle emission spectra measured at the University of   1325 1451
Maryland (Kalend et al. and Wu et al.) for 90-MeV protons, by     1325 1451
Meier at Los Alamos for 113-MeV protons, and Bertrand and Peelle  1325 1451
for 61-MeV protons are all reproduced reasonably by the present   1325 1451
analysis [Ch97].                                                  1325 1451
  Another useful test of our model calculations, particularly     1325 1451
for radionuclide production, can be made by comparing our         1325 1451
theoretical predictions of discrete gamma-ray emission in         1325 1451
Al27(n,xngamma) reactions with the recent LANSCE/WNR data taken   1325 1451
by Vonach, Haight, and collaborators [Vo94] using the white       1325 1451
neutron source. Preliminary comparisons show reasonably good      1325 1451
agreement.                                                        1325 1451
